    S.append(banner("PART 3 — SOCIAL MEDIA STRATEGY &amp; RETURN ON INVESTMENT (ROI)"))
    S.append(Spacer(1, 10))

    S += Q(15,
        "What are the TWO main purposes of social media use for organisations? Explain each with examples.",
        [
            "1. Social Media for Communication — To Convince and To Sell:",
            "Organisations use social media to communicate their brand message, promote products and services, manage their public image, and persuade audiences to take desired actions (purchase, sign up, visit a store). This purpose is primarily external-facing and tied to marketing and sales goals.",
            "Key questions for this purpose: What are we communicating? How do we measure its effectiveness? How does our audience perceive our message?",
            "Example: A retail company posting product videos, discount promotions, and customer testimonials on Instagram to drive online purchases.",
            "",
            "2. Social Media for Collaboration — To Work Together and To Share:",
            "Organisations use social media to facilitate teamwork, knowledge exchange, and collective problem-solving — both internally among employees and externally with customers, suppliers, and partners.",
            "Key questions for this purpose: How do we enable better collaboration? How do we capture and share collective knowledge?",
            "Example (internal): Using Yammer or Microsoft Teams to allow employees in different offices to collaborate on documents and share expertise.",
            "Example (external): A software company running a public community forum where customers help each other troubleshoot issues, share workflows, and suggest features.",
        ],
        "The two purposes: COMMUNICATION (external — convince & sell) and COLLABORATION (internal/external — share & work together). These drive all social media strategy decisions.")

    S += Q(16,
        "Define ROI in the context of social media marketing. Explain how organisations calculate and interpret it.",
        [
            "ROI stands for Return on Investment. In social media marketing, it measures the financial return generated by a social media investment relative to its cost. It answers the fundamental question: 'Is our social media spend worth it?'",
            "",
            "The ROI Formula:",
            "ROI = [ (Revenue generated - Cost of investment) / Cost of investment ] x 100%",
            "",
            "Steps to calculate social media ROI:",
            "- Step 1 — Identify the Cost: Include all direct and indirect costs (advertising spend, content creation, staff time, tools and software).",
            "- Step 2 — Measure Revenue Attributable to Social Media: Track which sales, leads, or conversions can be directly linked to social media activity (using tracking links, UTM codes, or coupon codes).",
            "- Step 3 — Apply the formula.",
            "",
            "Interpretation:",
            "- Positive ROI (e.g. +120%): The campaign generated more revenue than it cost — profitable.",
            "- ROI = 0%: Revenue exactly covered the cost — break-even.",
            "- Negative ROI (e.g. -30%): The campaign cost more than it returned — unprofitable.",
            "",
            "IT Management plays a central role in ROI calculation by using analytical techniques — including Social Network Analysis — to connect social actions (likes, shares, reach, comments) to business actions (website visits, purchases, customer retention).",
        ],
        "The ROI formula is always examined. Memorise: ROI = [(Revenue - Cost) / Cost] x 100%. Also know that IT Management uses SNA analytically to calculate this.")

    S += Q(17,
        "Explain the concepts of 'Time Shifting' and 'Space Shifting' as social media benefits. How do they relate to the Scalability advantage?",
        [
            "Time Shifting refers to the ability of social media content to be accessed at any time, day or night — 24 hours a day, 7 days a week (24/7). Unlike a television advertisement broadcast at a fixed time slot, or a shop that closes at 6pm, social media content is permanently available for audiences to view whenever it is convenient for them.",
            "",
            "Impact on organisations: They can publish content once and have it working for them continuously, reaching audiences across different time zones without additional effort. A post published in Cairo at 9am is accessible to a customer in Tokyo at any hour they choose to view it.",
            "",
            "Space Shifting refers to the ability of social media to transcend geographical boundaries, enabling a global marketplace. A small business in Fayoum can reach customers in London, New York, or Tokyo without having a physical office, distribution network, or advertising budget in those markets.",
            "",
            "Impact on organisations: Social media levels the playing field between large multinationals and small local businesses in terms of geographic reach.",
            "",
            "Relationship to Scalability: Both Time Shifting and Space Shifting are direct expressions of the Scalability advantage. Scalability means social media allows organisations to reach more people with lower budgets, unconstrained by time or geography — and Time Shifting + Space Shifting are the mechanisms through which this scalability is achieved.",
        ],
        "Time Shifting = 24/7 availability. Space Shifting = global reach. Both are why social media is 'scalable' beyond traditional media's limitations.")

    S += Q(18,
        "Describe how social media is used in the domain of IT Management. What role does Social Network Analysis (SNA) play?",
        [
            "In the IT Management domain, social media is used primarily in two interconnected ways:",
            "",
            "1. Supporting All Previous Domains: IT Management provides the technical infrastructure, platforms, tools, and integrations that enable every other business domain (marketing, HR, customer service, sales, accountancy) to operate effectively on social media. This includes selecting social media management platforms, CRM integrations, analytics dashboards, and security controls.",
            "",
            "2. Calculating and Justifying ROI: IT Management uses analytical techniques to monitor social media activity and calculate the Return on Investment of social media investments. This is done by correlating:",
            "- Social Actions: likes, shares, comments, reach, impressions, follower growth, mentions",
            "- Business Actions: website visits, form completions, product purchases, customer support ticket reduction, employee collaboration improvements",
            "",
            "The role of SNA (Social Network Analysis): SNA provides the mathematical and computational framework for mapping the relationships and information flows within social media networks. IT Management uses SNA to:",
            "- Identify the most influential users (high centrality nodes) whose engagement has the greatest amplification effect.",
            "- Understand how information spreads through the network — which connections act as bridges or bottlenecks.",
            "- Measure network growth, density, and community formation over time.",
            "- Connect social network metrics to financial business outcomes to demonstrate the ROI of social media.",
        ],
        "IT Management = infrastructure + ROI calculation using SNA. The link between social actions (likes) and business actions (sales) is what SNA enables.")

    S.append(PageBreak())

    # ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    # PART 4 — DIGITAL MARKETING & ONLINE ADVERTISING
