    S.append(Spacer(1, 10))

    S += Q(19,
        "Explain the relationship between SEM, SEA, and SEO. Define each term and describe their differences.",
        [
            "SEM — Search Engine Marketing: The umbrella term encompassing all marketing activities conducted through or related to search engines. It has two main branches: SEA and SEO.",
            "",
            "SEA — Search Engine Advertising (the Paid Branch): Organisations pay to have their advertisements displayed prominently (typically at the top or bottom) of search engine results pages. The most common payment model is Pay-Per-Click (PPC) — the advertiser pays each time a user clicks on the ad. Results appear immediately once the campaign is active, but stop the moment the budget runs out.",
            "",
            "SEO — Search Engine Optimisation (the Organic/Free Branch): The process of improving a website's content, technical structure, and external authority (backlinks) so that it naturally ranks higher in search results without paying per click. SEO takes longer to achieve results but provides sustainable, ongoing traffic at no direct cost per visitor.",
            "",
            "Hierarchy: SEM is the parent category. SEA is the paid child. SEO is the organic child.",
            "",
            "Key differences:",
            "- Cost: SEA = paid per click. SEO = no direct cost per click.",
            "- Speed: SEA = immediate results. SEO = gradual, long-term results.",
            "- Sustainability: SEA stops when budget ends. SEO continues after effort is invested.",
            "- Trust: Organic SEO results are generally perceived as more trustworthy by users than paid ads.",
            "",
            "Best practice: Most organisations use both together — SEA for immediate visibility on high-priority terms, and SEO for long-term organic dominance.",
        ],
        "The hierarchy: SEM = SEA + SEO. SEA = Advertising (paid). SEO = Optimisation (organic/free). Draw the tree diagram in the exam.")

    S += Q(20,
        "What is the purpose of Virtual World tools in social media? How can organisations use them, and what are their limitations?",
        [
            "Virtual World tools are immersive, three-dimensional digital environments where users create avatars (digital representations of themselves) and interact with others in a simulated physical space. These platforms allow users to meet, talk, exchange ideas, watch presentations, and participate in shared experiences in a virtual setting.",
            "",
            "Examples: Second Life, Kaneva.",
            "",
            "How organisations can use Virtual Worlds:",
            "- Virtual Conferences and Press Events: Organisations can host press conferences, product launches, or shareholder meetings in a virtual building without the travel and logistics costs of physical events.",
            "- Virtual Showrooms and Stores: Brands can create interactive virtual product experiences where users can 'walk through' and explore products.",
            "- Virtual Training: Employees in different countries can participate in immersive training sessions simultaneously.",
            "- Brand Building: Creating a branded virtual space establishes a persistent presence accessible to users at any time.",
            "",
            "Limitations:",
            "- Adoption Barrier: Virtual worlds require users to download software and invest time in learning the platform — a high barrier compared to simply clicking a link.",
            "- Niche Audience: The mainstream audience has largely moved away from platforms like Second Life toward simpler social media tools.",
            "- Technical Requirements: High-quality virtual world experiences require good hardware and internet connections.",
        ],
        "Virtual worlds are niche but innovative. Examples: Second Life. Key uses: press conferences, virtual stores, training, brand experiences.")

    S += Q(21,
        "Describe Live Casting tools and Productivity tools in social media. Give examples and explain the value for organisations.",
        [
            "Live Casting Tools: Platforms that broadcast video in real time, usually available for free. Unlike pre-recorded video, live casting shows events as they happen — similar to live television but on the internet.",
            "",
            "Examples: Live365, Justin.tv.",
